          "body": "Into the middle of a sustained judgment oracle, the prophetic community interrupts with a doxology: 'Our Redeemer, the LORD of hosts is His name, the Holy One of Israel' (47:4). This single verse does more theological work than any other in the chapter. It identifies the speaker of the oracle — not a prophet enjoying an enemy's downfall, but the *goel*, the kinsman-redeemer with the legal right and familial obligation to avenge His enslaved people. The *goel* concept in Hebrew law (Leviticus 25:25; Ruth 4:1-6) was the mechanism by which a family member bought back a relative sold into slavery and avenged blood that had been wrongly shed. YHWH is doing both here: He is buying Israel back from Babylon (cf. 43:3; 52:3) and taking vengeance on the one who enslaved them (47:3). The doxology also inserts the name 'the Holy One of Israel' — the title Isaiah uses more than any other prophet (25 times in Isaiah against 6 elsewhere in the OT). Babylon's sin of claiming 'I am, and there is no one besides me' is offensive precisely to the One whose holiness is absolute and whose name is incomparable. John Calvin notes that every act of divine judgment is simultaneously a vindication of divine holiness — God cannot be indifferent to what His name is called, because His name is His character."
