          "title": "The three sins of empire — cruelty, pride, and the divine formula",
          "body": "The indictment of verses 6-10 isolates three specific charges with precision. First: cruelty beyond mandate. YHWH explicitly acknowledges that He delivered Israel into Babylon's hand (47:6) — the exile was His disciplinary act. But Babylon exceeded that authorization. She showed no mercy and made the yoke 'very heavy' on the aged, the most vulnerable. This is the charge that appears repeatedly in prophetic literature against nations YHWH uses as instruments: Assyria in Isaiah 10:5-19 is condemned for the same excess of cruelty despite being YHWH's appointed 'rod of anger.' The instrument is not exempt from accountability for how it swings. Second: presumptuous eternalism. 'I will be a queen forever' (47:7) takes the word *olam* — eternity — and applies it to a human institution. In Isaiah's theology, *olam* belongs exclusively to YHWH: 'I am the first and I am the last, and there is no God besides Me' (44:6). To claim *olam* is to claim what belongs to the Eternal One. Third, and most severe: Babylon twice uses the precise formula YHWH uses of His own uniqueness — 'I am, and there is no one besides me' (47:8, 10; cf. 45:5-6, 18, 22). Douglas Moo's observation about New Testament idolatry applies here in its Old Testament form: the deepest idolatry is not worshiping something grotesque but attributing to a creature the self-sufficiency that belongs to the Creator."
